\begin{align*}
7 \text{ ligs }&= 4 \text{ lags }\\
9 \text{ lags }&= 20 \text{ lugs }
\end{align*}
Now, we are given 80 lugs. We can find the equivalent lags:
$\frac{20 \text{ lugs}}{9 \text{ lags }} = \frac{80 \text{ lugs }}{?}$
This means for every 9 lags we get 20 lugs, so for every 1 lag, we get $\frac{20}{9}$ lugs. We want 80 lugs, which means we want $\frac{80}{\frac{20}{9}}$ distance of lags. That will be $\frac{80}{\frac{20}{9}} = 36$. We got 36 lags, but what we want are ligs. We already found a relation between ligs and lags: $7 \text{ ligs }= 4 \text{ lags }$. To find the equivalent ligs, we divide by 4 on both sides. We get 1 lag is equal to $\frac{7}{4}$ ligs. So, $36 \text{ lags } = \frac{36 \times 7}{4} = 63$ ligs. There are $\boxed{63}$ ligs equivalent to 80 lugs.###
